{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508080"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:01:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:01:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2713"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2713"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.12,0.2,0.28,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2713"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46973"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2713"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2713"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31735"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"240"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"6238"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3414"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3478"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27800"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46973"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of excruciating chest pain. His symptoms are worse when he breathes. This pain began immediately after an episode of vomiting brought on by a large meal and many drinks at a party. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he looks unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/65 mmHg, temperature 37.2\u00b0C and SpO2 96% on room air. There is palpable crepitus at the base of his neck and dullness to percussion of the left chest base. A CT with oral contrast is performed (Image). Intravenous fluids and antibiotics are started.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continued observation","Nasogastric tube insertion and drainage","Chest drain","Oesophageal mesh stent","Thoracotomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture is of a spontaneous perforation of the oesophagus (Boerhaave\u0027s syndrome). The palpable crepitus in the neck is subcutaneous emphysema and this will have come either from the respiratory or digestive tract. The diagnosis is confirmed with the observation of contrast leaking out of the oesophagus and into the left chest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrgent and aggressive intervention is required before the chemical and bacterial contamination of the mediastinum and left pleural cavity lead to an overwhelming systemic inflammatory response and thence septic shock, therefore \u003Cstrong\u003Econtinued observation \u003C/strong\u003Eis entirely inappropriate in this case. After a \u0027large meal\u0027 there is likely gross soiling of the left pleural cavity and only a \u003Cstrong\u003Ethoracotomy\u003C/strong\u003E will deal with this. Lavage and debridement are urgently required with repair of the oesophageal defect to prevent ongoing soiling and drainage of the chest as many repairs leak in the presence of a poor blood supply, hypotension and sepsis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enasogastric tube\u003C/strong\u003E might empty the stomach, but will not prevent saliva and other swallowed material from entering the chest. It will be instead placed during surgery. Placement pre-surgery will have a high likelihood of entering the chest cavity anyhow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest drain\u003C/strong\u003E may drain material out of the chest and whilst this should be part of the management, it will do nothing to prevent continued oesophageal leakage. In the absence of such clear symptoms, signs and radiology, it is an unnecessary initial step unless there is a tension hydro-pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMany authors have documented success in case reports using expandable \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophageal mesh stents\u003C/strong\u003E. However, these will not deal with the life-threatening contamination that is common in Boerhaave type perforations. In carefully selected patients, where there has been minimal contamination of the pleural space then they may play a role but this was not their intended use and migration rates are high.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll cases such as this should be managed by a specialist Upper GI surgical team.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Crepitus in the neck points to leakage from either the respiratory or the gastrointestinal tract."],"references":["Allaway MGR, Morris PD, Sinclair J-L B, et al. Management of Boerhaave syndrome in Australasia: a retrospective case series and systematic review of the Australasian literature. ANZ J Surg 2021; 91:1376\u201384."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31735"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2713"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15284"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15284"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fab49c1e-851f-40b9-be4f-08357bf05703.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fab49c1e-851f-40b9-be4f-08357bf05703.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":512,"height":410}},{"